{In this chapter, we deal with Black's most aggressive response to Bird's,
From's Gambit. From the get go, Black offers us a pawn for an instant
development lead and attacking chances. Now when I played} 1. f4 {online in
2005 to 2006, From's was the most common response from titled players. Today,
having taken up Bird's opening again, I haven't had a single From's Gambit
from a titled player - in fact, I haven't had anyone play it! The reason: It
is currently in theoretical disrepair and the fun-killing comps have pretty
much worked it out in White's favour. A gambit with the black pieces is a
tricky entity, since we as White already get a one move development head start,
which in turn decreases Black's compensation. Be warned though, at the club
level it is still quite popular. If you know your lines, you should be able to
pull out a clear advantage. Still, such positions, even though borderline
unsound for Black, are not so easy to play for our side, since we are thrown
on the defensive for such a long time. So even though we have an advantage
over the board, Black, in a certain sense, still retains the practical chances.
So let's not underestimate this line. Tossed into such murk, we deal in
"maybe" and "I'm-not-so-sure", more than fixed notions. Our difficulties can
be encapsulated into a single issue: King safety. If you test the positions
against the comps, taking Black, you will soon master the art of snatching
Black's gift pawn and converting it to the full point.} *

